<h2>Illustrations by Charles Kingsley</h2> 
<img src="../../../icons2/vntop.gif"/>
<p class="bc">
[<a href ="../../../index.html">Victorian Web Home</a> —> 
<a href="../../index.html">Visual Arts</a> —> 
<a href= "../index.html">Illustration</a> —> 
<a href="../../../authors/kingsley/index.html">Kingsley as author</a>]</p>

</div>

<div id="main">



<p class="one">Kingsley’s significant contribution to Victorian culture as a social commentator and writer has been examined in great detail. Barely noted, however, is his interest in painting; an amateur artist, who practised in landscape and genre, he was knowledgeable of the History of Art and had well-defined ideas on the aesthetics and role of book illustration. He was also the illustrator of a single book, <span class="book">The Heroes</span>, a simplified gloss on the Greek myths. — <a href="../../../misc/cooke.html">Simon Cooke</a>
</p>

<a href="3.html"><img src="3.jpg" height="230" class="floatright"/></a>


